Unfortunately, it seems we have some missing data.

Testing for Normality

In the following, Shapiro-Wilks test of normality will be used on all panels of cytokines to determine whether data is normally distributed or not. We will be testing the differences between baseline and day 5. We need data to be approximately normally distributed in order to perform paired T-tests. If Shapiro-Wilks test evaluates non-normal distribution, manual inspection and evaluation of QQ-plots and histograms will be performed in order to evaluation normality of data.

Angiogenesis panel

Shapiro Wilks Test

# Define function for Shapiro-Wilk test
# x == panel currently inspecting
func.swilk.panel <- function(x) {
  df.cytokines.wide %>% filter(
  panel == x) %>% 
  group_by(sample) %>% 
  shapiro_test(difference) %>% 
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), round, 5)) %>% 
  as.data.frame()
}

# Shapiro Wilks test
func.swilk.panel("angiogenesis")

Data is normally distributed except Tie-2. Lets do a manual inspection.

Outliers

First, we can check for outliers by using this function.

# Create function to identify outliers in dataset "df.cytokines.wide"
# Outliers are based upon differences between baseline and day 5.
func.outlier <- function(x) {
df.cytokines.wide %>%
  filter(
    sample == x) %>% 
  identify_outliers(difference)
}

# Check for outliers, sample == Tie-2
func.outlier("Tie-2")

For subject 18, the difference in Tie-2 values from baseline to day 5 differs greatly compared to the rest of the populations differences. Thus, we have significant outliers in the data for Tie-2 samples.

Now lets visually inspect the data for Tie-2 data

QQ-plotting and histograms

# Create function for plotting QQ-plots and histograms
func.qqhisto <- function(x) {
  hist(df.cytokines.wide$difference[df.cytokines.wide$sample == x],
       main = x)
  plot <- ggqqplot(
    df.cytokines.wide$difference[df.cytokines.wide$sample == x],
    main = x,
    ggtheme = theme_grey())
  print(plot)
}

func.qqhisto("Tie-2")

Histogram

Histogram is highly skewed with the extreme outlier to the left.

QQ-plot

Again, we have an extreme outlier as also showed above. Otherwise, data seems to follow a normal distribution.

Conclusion

It does not seem safe to assume approximate normal distribution for sample Tie-2.

Boxplots

# This is formula for a single boxplot using base R boxplot()
boxplot(angio_bfgf ~ visit_type,
        data = df.cytokines,
        main = "Title",
        xlab = "Title X-axis"
        )


# Define function for batch processing
func.boxplots <- function(x) {
  for (cytokine in x) { 
    boxplot(cytokine ~ visit_type,
            data = df.cytokines,
            xlab = "Visit")
      }
}
# "cytokine" = unique variable
# "x" = a list, for which the function will loop through

# Loop for making dataframes with each panel type in wide format
for (panel in c("angio", "chemo", "cyto", "pro", "vasc")) {
  assign(paste0("df.vars.", panel), df.cytokines[grep(panel, colnames(df.cytokines))])
}
# Show one dataframe loop above has produced
df.vars.pro
